==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[https://larrysharpe.com Larry Sharpe for Governor]\n*[https://www.c-span.org/person/?larrysharpe Appearances] on [[C-SPAN]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Michael McDermott (politician)|Michael McDermott]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title = [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] nominee for [[Governor of New York]]|years=[[New York gubernatorial election, 2018|2018]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{2020 United States presidential election}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharpe, Larry}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American educators]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:2016 United States vice-presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:2020 United States vice-presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:African-American company founders]]\n[[Category:African-American educators]]\n[[Category:African-American military personnel]]\n[[Category:African-American people in New York (state) politics]]\n[[Category:American adoptees]]\n[[Category:American cannabis activists]]\n[[Category:American gun rights activists]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Drug policy reform activists]]\n[[Category:Educators from New York City]]\n[[Category:Internet people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Libertarian Party (United States)]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Libertarians]]\n[[Category:Non-interventionism]]\n[[Category:People from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Politicians from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:United States Marines]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland Global Campus alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Larry Sharpe\n| image              = Larry Sharpe portrait.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Larry David Sharpe\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1968|07|12}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York (city)|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Astoria, Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| nationality        = \n| citizenship        = \n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = {{bulleted list|2018 Libertarian Party candidate for [[New York gubernatorial election, 2018|Governor of New York]]|2016 Libertarian Party [[2016 Libertarian National Convention#Vice presidential delegate count|vice presidential candidate]]}}\n| education          = [[University of Maryland University College]] (B.A.)\n| occupation         = Business consultant\n| years_active       = \n| home_town          = \n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]]\n| opponents          = \n| boards             = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = 2\n| parents            = \n| relations          = \n| callsign           = \n| website            ={{url|larrysharpe.com/}}\n| awards             = \n| signature          = \n| footnotes          = \n| box_width          = \n| module             = {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n|allegiance = United States\n|branch=United States Marine Corps\n|serviceyears= 1986\u20131993\n|rank = [[File:USMC-E6.svg|18px]] [[Staff sergeant]]\n}}\n}}\n{{Libertarianism sidebar}}\n'''Larry David Sharpe''' (born July 12, 1968) is an American business consultant, entrepreneur, political activist, and [[Streaming media|internet broadcaster]]. He was a candidate for the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] nomination for Vice President of the United States in [[2016 Libertarian National Convention|2016]], losing narrowly to former Massachusetts Governor [[Bill Weld]]. Sharpe was also the Libertarian nominee for [[Governor of New York]] in the [[New York gubernatorial election, 2018|2018 gubernatorial election]]. Sharpe is the founder and managing director of the online business training company Neo-Sage Group, Inc.\n\n==Early life and career==\nSharpe was born on July 12, 1968 in Manhattan, New York and was adopted as an infant. He joined the [[United States Marines Corps]] at age 17,<ref name=\"Reason VP\"/> and he received a Bachelor's Degree in [[Anthropology]] from the [[University of Maryland University College]].<ref name=\"LPConvention\"/> After working as an English teacher, Sharpe founded Prime Distribution Inc. (a trucking and distribution company which he later sold) in 2001.<ref name=\"Meet Larry\">{{Citation|title=Meet Larry Sharpe|accessdate=August 13, 2018|url=https://larrysharpe.com/bio/|publisher=Larry Sharpe for Governor}}</ref> In 2004, Sharpe built an online business training company called Neo-Sage Group, Inc.,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sharpe|first1=Larry|url=http://www.sharpe4vp.com/issues|title=Issues|website=Sharpe4VP.com|accessdate=December 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.neo-sage-forum.com|title=Neo-Sage Forum|website=Neo-sage-forum.com|accessdate=July 17, 2018}}</ref> for which he serves as managing director.<ref name=\"Reason VP\">[[Brian Doherty (journalist)|Doherty, Brian]] {{Citation|title=''\"Meet the Libertarian Party's VP Candidates\"''|accessdate=December 3, 2016|date=May 28, 2016|url=http://reason.com/blog/2016/05/28/the-libertarian-partys-vice-presidential|work=Reason}}</ref><ref name=\"LPConvention\">{{Citation|author=Libertarian Party|title=Larry Sharpe|accessdate=December 3, 2016|url=http://libertarian.nationbuilder.com/sharpe|publisher=Libertarian Party}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nAs a Libertarian Party activist, Sharpe has outlined a vision to grow the party by encouraging [[grassroots]] Libertarian Party campaigns across the country.<ref name=\"Reason\">[[Matt Welch|Welch, Matt]] {{Citation|title=''\"Selling Liberty\"''|accessdate=January 19, 2018|date=February 2018|url=http://reason.com/archives/2018/01/14/selling-freedom|work=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]}}</ref> Sharpe served on the [[Libertarian National Committee]] as the Alternate for Region 8, until his resignation in February 2018 because of an internal LNC vote that failed to oust the party's then-vice chair, [[Arvin Vohra]], following public controversial comments made by Vohra.<ref name=\"Resigns\">{{Citation|last=Doherty|first=Brian|title=''\"Larry Sharpe, Libertarian Candidate for Governor of New York, Quits the Party's National Committee\"''|accessdate=February 20, 2018|date=February 7, 2018|url=https://reason.com/blog/2018/02/07/larry-sharpe-libertarian-candidate-for-g|work=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]}}</ref>\n\n===2016 vice presidential campaign===\n{{main|2016 Libertarian National Convention#Vice presidential delegate count}}\nSharpe was a candidate for the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]] Libertarian vice presidential nomination. During the [[2016 Libertarian National Convention]], he placed second on the first ballot with 30.4% of the vote. Because no one received a majority on that ballot, a second ballot vote was held.<ref name=\"C-SPAN Live\">{{cite web|title=Will Coley drops out and endorses Sharpe for LP VP|website=[[C-SPAN]]|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4601302/will-coley-drops-endorses-sharpe-lp-vp|date=May 29, 2016|accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref> Sharpe received 46.9% of the vote on the second ballot, finishing second to former [[Governor of Massachusetts|Massachusetts Governor]] [[Bill Weld]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Here's What Happened at the Libertarian National Convention|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PioXdolPGCw}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lyman|first=Andy|title= Naked candidates, frosty delegates and choosing a candidate: The quest for the White House|website=NM Political Report|url= http://nmpoliticalreport.com/47889/naked-candidates-frosty-delegates-and-setting-the-table-for-dinner-the-quest-for-the-white-house/|date=June 4, 2016|accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018 New York gubernatorial campaign===\n{{main|New York gubernatorial election, 2018}}\nOn July 12, 2017, Sharpe announced his 2018 candidacy for Governor of New York, making him the first person to mount a challenge to incumbent Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Spector|first=Joseph|url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/2017/12/12/brian-kolb-bid-ny-governor/943458001/|title=Kolb becomes first Republican to officially announce run against Cuomo|website=[[Democrat and Chronicle]]|date=December 12, 2017|accessdate=December 15, 2017}}</ref> Sharpe received the Libertarian nomination on April 21, 2018 and Andrew Hollister was selected as the [[Lieutenant Governor of New York|Lieutenant Governor]] nominee for the ticket.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lpnewyork.org/2018/04/22/lpny-holds-annual-convention/|title=LPNY Holds 46th Annual Convention; Larry Sharpe Nominated for Governor \u2013 Libertarian Party of New York|date=April 22, 2018|website=Lpnewyork.org|accessdate=April 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSharpe's campaign raised $102,596 prior to the first filing deadline, which was second to Andrew Cuomo's re-election campaign.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mahoney|first=Bill|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/albany/story/2018/01/25/a-new-york-rarity-a-serious-libertarian-candidate-212763?__s=dbm6j6fzp8msbjcg2gyq|title=A New York rarity: A serious Libertarian candidate|website=[[Politico]]|date=January 25, 2018|accessdate=January 30, 2018}}</ref> As of October 10, 2018, Sharpe raised $449,515 for his campaign, the highest amount ever raised by a Libertarian gubernatorial candidate in New York. Sharpe in addition was the only candidate in the race to have visited all 62 counties on the campaign trail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://reason.com/blog/2018/10/31/libertarian-larry-sharpe-has-raised-a-re|title=Libertarian Larry Sharpe Has Raised a Record $450,000 in New York Governor's Race|author=Welch, Matt|date=October 31, 2018|accessdate=November 11, 2018|work=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]}}</ref>\n\nOn Election Day, Sharpe received 95,033 votes (1.6%) and came in fourth place behind Cuomo, Republican challenger [[Marc Molinaro]], and [[Green Party of New York|Green Party]] candidate [[Howie Hawkins]]. Sharpe's vote total achieved [[Qualified New York political parties|automatic ballot access]] for the [[Libertarian Party of New York]] for the first time in the party's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsmax.com/newsfront/larry-sharpe-new-york-libertarian-ballot/2018/11/07/id/889825/|title=Libertarian Party Gets Ballot Line in NY State|author=Reyner, Solange|date=November 7, 2018|accessdate=November 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Endorsements box\n| title = Endorsements\n| list =\n;U.S. Governors\n* [[Gary Johnson]], former [[Governor of New Mexico]] and [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] presidential nominee in [[Gary Johnson presidential campaign, 2012|2012]] and [[Gary Johnson presidential campaign, 2016|2016]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qjepuZkfyuo|title=Gary Johnson Endorses Larry Sharpe for NY Governor|date=October 26, 2017|accessdate=October 28, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[William Weld]], former [[Governor of Massachusetts]] and [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] vice-presidential nominee in 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thejacknews.com/politics/political-highlights/gov-bill-weld-endorses-larry-sharpe-for-governor-of-new-york-at-students-for-liberty-conference/|title=Governor Bill Weld Endorses Larry Sharpe for Governor of New York at SFL Conference|date=November 6, 2017|accessdate=November 8, 2017|work=TheJackNews|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109023255/https://www.thejacknews.com/politics/political-highlights/gov-bill-weld-endorses-larry-sharpe-for-governor-of-new-york-at-students-for-liberty-conference/|archive-date=November 9, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n;U.S. municipal legislators\n* William Brooke Harris, Republican [[Allegany County, New York|Allegany County]] legislator<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsgrowl.com/brooke-harris-endorses-larry-sharpe/|title=Brooke Harris becomes first elected NY GOP official to endorse Larry Sharpe for governor|date=July 17, 2018|accessdate=July 17, 2018|author=Goodale, Steve|work=News Growl}}</ref>\n;Other politicians\n* Craig Bowden, 2018 Libertarian candidate for U.S. Senate from Utah<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bowden4senate.com/2018/02/03/endorsement-larry-sharpe/|title=ENDORSEMENT \u2013 LARRY SHARPE|author=Bowden, Craig|accessdate=February 3, 2018|date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n* Joseph Byrne, Trustee on the [[Valley Central School District]] Board of Education<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=331783104240527&set=a.119343625484477|title=Joseph Byrne|website=Facebook.com|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n* Michelle Darnell, 2017 [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] candidate for [[Washington (state)|Washington State]] Representative<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=1976774759274875&id=100008271105758|title=Michelle Darnell|website=Facebook.com|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n* Dale Kerns, 2018 [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] candidate for [[United States Senate election in Pennsylvania, 2018|Pennsylvania Senator]]\n* [[Kash Jackson]], Navy veteran and activist, Libertarian nominee for [[Illinois Governor]] [[Illinois gubernatorial election, 2018|2018]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TeaPartyerRhian/status/970820155382161408|title=Twitter|website=Twitter|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Michael McDermott (politician)|Michael McDermott]], [[New York gubernatorial election, 2014|2014]] Libertarian nominee for [[Governor of New York]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/michael.mcdermott.1460/posts/10211990781544996|title=Michael McDermott|website=Facebook.com|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Austin Petersen]], [[United States Senate election in Missouri, 2018|2018]] Republican candidate for U.S. Senate in Missouri and [[2016 Libertarian National Convention|2016]] Libertarian candidate for President of the United States<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AP4Liberty/status/1027038545716895744|title=Austin Petersen on Twitter|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n* Stevan Porter, [[United States House of Representatives elections in Virginia, 2018#District 11|2018]] Libertarian candidate for [[Virginia's 11th congressional district]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Porter4Us/status/1041816028739776512|title=Stevan Porter on Twitter|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n* James Tosone, 2018 Libertarian nominee for United States Congress, New Jersey District 5<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/tosone4congress/status/1013886428634378241|title=Tosone4Congress on Twitter|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=July 17, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n* James Rosenbeck, chairman of the [[Libertarian Party of New York]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailynewsonline.com/bdn06/larry-sharpe-can-win-on-election-day-20181031|title=Larry Sharpe can win on election day|author=Rosenbeck, James|date=October 31, 2018|accessdate=October 31, 2018|work=The Daily News}}</ref>\n* [[Nickolas Wildstar]], 2018 [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] candidate for [[California gubernatorial election, 2018|Governor of California]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c-AvQFoKm5w|title=Wildstar Endorses Larry Sharpe For Governor|date=September 19, 2017|accessdate=November 8, 2017}}</ref>\n;Television and radio personalities\n* [[Glenn Beck]], conservative political commentator and radio host at [[TheBlaze]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://omny.fm/shows/the-glenn-beck-program/best-of-the-program-with-larry-sharpe-10-1-18|title=Best of the Program with Larry Sharpe \u2013 10/1/18 \u2013 Glenn Beck \u2013 Omny.fm|website=Omny.fm|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}</ref>\n* Shannon Joy, [[WYSL]] radio host<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/shannon.wysl/posts/1061478290673151|title=Shannon Joy|website=Facebook.com|accessdate=July 17, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Joanne Nosuchinsky]], 2013 [[Miss USA 2013|Miss New York USA]] and co-host of Mornin'!!! with Bill Schulz<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JoNosuchinsky/status/1057297224672178178|title=Joanne Nosuchinsky on Twitter|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=November 8, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Evan Roberts (radio personality)|Evan Roberts]], sports radio talk personality and co-host of ''[[Joe & Evan]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/EvanRobertsWFAN/status/1058835213638397953|title=Evan Roberts on Twitter|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=November 8, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Joe Rogan]], comedian, [[mixed martial arts]] [[color commentator]], [[podcast]] host, and businessman<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nSmggQZno6w|title=Joe Rogan Experience #1167 \u2013 Larry Sharpe|date=September 5, 2018|accessdate=November 8, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n* [[Dave Rubin]], political commentator and talk show host, creator and host of [[The Rubin Report]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RTj8ZoCiM4E|title=A Libertarian Running for Governor of New York (Larry Sharpe Full Interview)|date=July 13, 2018|accessdate=November 8, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n* [[Bill Schulz]], journalist, television personality and host of Mornin'!!! with Bill Schulz<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BillSchulz/status/1057068834316828672|title=Bill Schulz on Twitter|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=November 8, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Katherine Timpf]], comedian, reporter and [[Fox News]] television personality<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bESZo3jdz54|title=Gutfeld: Why election stress only damages the left|date=November 3, 2018|accessdate=November 8, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n;Commentators, writers, and columnists\n* Bob Confer, columnist for the [[Lockport Union-Sun & Journal]] and the [[Niagara Gazette]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.niagara-gazette.com/opinion/confer-the-sharpest-candidate-for-governor/article_5b3a69c8-de0f-532a-8ab1-a4acad7d6987.html|title=CONFER: The sharpest candidate for governor|author=Confer, Bob|date=September 19, 2018|accessdate=September 23, 2018|newspaper=[[Niagara Gazette]]}}</ref>\n* Jeremy Frankel, writer for [[The Daily Wire]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/FrankelJeremy/status/1040578662456811521|title=Jeremy \"Spartacus\" Frankel on Twitter|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n* [[John Stossel]], author, journalist and libertarian news commentator<ref>{{cite web|url=https://triblive.com/opinion/featuredcommentary/14242568-74/john-stossel-libertarian-has-sharp-ideas-for-ny|title=John Stossel: Libertarian has sharp ideas for NY|date=November 2, 2018|accessdate=November 2, 2018|work=Trib Live|author=Stossel, John}}</ref>\n* [[Matt Welch]], journalist at [[Reason (magazine)|''Reason'']]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MattWelch/status/1059894512468803585|title=Matt Welch on Twitter|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=November 8, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n;Musicians and artists\n* [[Gerald Walker]], hip-hop musician<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/WalkWithGerald/status/1050916223607816192|title=Gerald Walker on Twitter|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=November 8, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n;Athletes and sports figures\n* [[Aron Price]], professional golfer<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/aronpricePGA/status/1046368355479945217|title=Aron Price on Twitter|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n;Social and political activists\n* Matthew Kolken, immigration lawyer and elected member of the [[American Immigration Lawyers Association|AILA]] board of directors<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mkolken/status/1045350423891251201|title=Matthew Kolken on Twitter|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n;Organizations\n* 71Republic<ref>{{cite web|url=https://71republic.com/2018/06/03/dear-new-york-elect-larry-sharpe/|title=Dear New York: Elect Larry Sharpe \u2013 71 Republic|date=June 3, 2018|website=71republic.com|accessdate=July 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613184130/https://71republic.com/2018/06/03/dear-new-york-elect-larry-sharpe/|archive-date=June 13, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Libertarian Youth Caucus<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/LYCaucus/posts/2251222821764174?__xts__%5B0%5D=68.ARDi628ETLyOpTcW4kIb0HznfDKTd6vfu2rOq6EnQ1AzhYUkVn8o_4ffrC2caUDWW-zxoihe0HZtp3wslnB4sZ7tVjC8D-SMPWspcVbyapkdUNIi1ad6Nl1DXHCABHLfcC00l2fD0r4-9ZxTicmdLYbEFh74lUAHRJiILN-OHnOdX1SDBkQoTg&__tn__=C-R|title=Libertarian Youth Caucus|website=Facebook.com|accessdate=November 8, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n* Marijuana Reform Party of New York state<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mailchi.mp/cannabis4ny.org/apologies-to-our-republican-libertarian-and-independent-supporters|title=Apologies to Our Republican, Libertarian and Independent Supporters|website=Mailchi.mp|accessdate=July 17, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Monroe County, New York|Monroe County]] Libertarian Party<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/MonroeCountyLibertarianParty/posts/1857286200949757|title=Monroe County Libertarian Party|website=Facebook.com|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Onondaga County, New York|Onondaga County]] Libertarian Party<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lpnewyork.org/2018/04/10/onondaga-lp-chapter-endorses-candidates-elects-officers/|title=Onondaga LP Chapter Endorses Candidates, Elects Officers|author=Kolstee, Andrew|date=April 10, 2018|accessdate=April 13, 2018|work=Libertarian Party of New York|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180414010358/https://lpnewyork.org/2018/04/10/onondaga-lp-chapter-endorses-candidates-elects-officers/|archive-date=April 14, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Otsego County, New York|Otsego County]] Libertarian Party<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/LP_OtsegoCounty/status/1046149194254290946|title=OtsegoCountyLibertarians on Twitter|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=October 4, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n====Post-campaign activities====\nFollowing the 2018 election, Sharpe continued speaking tours across New York State.<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/pg/Sharpe4Gov/events/ Larry Sharpe, Libertarian - Events]</ref> In 2019, he launched ''The Sharpe Way'', an [[Webcast|online talk show]].<ref>[https://sharpeway.com/ The Sharpe Way]</ref>\n\n===2020 vice presidential campaign===\nOn April 13, 2020 it was announced that Sharpe would again seek the Libertarian Party's nomination for Vice President, as the running mate of 2012 Libertarian vice-presidential nominee [[James P. Gray|Judge Jim Gray]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://reason.com/2020/04/13/judge-jim-gray-to-seek-libertarian-presidential-nomination/|title=Judge Jim Gray To Seek Libertarian Presidential Nomination|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 13, 2020|work=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]|author=Welch, Matt}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nSharpe supports reducing regulations such as [[occupational licensing]] as well as legalizing marijuana and decriminalizing other drugs.<ref name=\"WAER\">{{cite web|authors=Willis, Scott, Liam McMonagle, and Chris Bolt|url=http://waer.org/post/libertarian-candidate-gov-i-have-solutions-problems-two-party-system-cant-solve?__s=dbm6j6fzp8msbjcg2gyq|title=Libertarian Candidate for Gov: I have Solutions to Problems that Two Party System Can't Solve|publisher=[[WAER]]|date=February 19, 2018|accessdate=February 20, 2018}}</ref> Sharpe has advocated for raising revenue for New York by selling naming rights to bridges and highways.<ref name=\"Binghamton\">{{cite web|url=http://www.binghamtonhomepage.com/news/local-news/larry-sharpe-expected-to-receive-libertarian-party-endorsement-for-governor/1063155982|title=Larry Sharpe expected to receive Libertarian Party endorsement for Governor|website=Binghamton Homepage|date=March 20, 2018|accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Abortion===\nSharpe considers himself \"[[pro-choice]]\" as well as \"anti-abortion\". While running for Governor, he vowed to reduce the number of abortions in New York state by increasing availability of other options instead of establishing regulations on abortion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wxxinews.org/post/connections-gubernatorial-candidate-larry-sharpe|title=Coming up on Connections: Friday, September 14|author1=Mack, Megan|author2=Dawson, Evan|date=September 14, 2018|accessdate=September 14, 2018|work=WXXI News}}</ref>\n\n===Criminal justice===\nSharpe favors [[marijuana legalization]], calling for [[hemp]] and marijuana to be \"regulated like onions\".<ref name=Ithaca>{{cite web|url=https://www.ithaca.com/news/libertarian-candidate-for-governor-larry-sharpe-visits-tompkins-county/article_bbc751b8-8116-11e8-931a-9b912d3a9938.html|title=Libertarian candidate for Governor Larry Sharpe visits Tompkins County|author=Reynolds, Nick|date=July 6, 2018|accessdate=August 14, 2018|work=Ithaca.com}}</ref> Sharpe has said he would [[pardon]] those convicted of [[victimless crime]]s or otherwise non-violent offenses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waer.org/post/libertarian-candidate-gov-i-have-solutions-problems-two-party-system-cant-solve|title=Libertarian Candidate for Gov: I have Solutions to Problems that Two Party System Can't Solve|author1=Willis, Scott|author2=McMonagle, Liam|author3=Bolt, Chris|date=February 19, 2018|accessdate=August 25, 2018|work=WAER 88.3}}</ref>\n\n===Economy===\nSharpe has supported [[deregulation]] to stimulate economic growth, ending the funding of enforcement of unnecessary regulations. In particular, Sharpe has cited [[occupational licensing]] as a hurdle to small business, describing mandatory licensing for jobs such as barbers and dog walkers as \"barriers to entry and a tax on the poor.\"<ref name= paternalgovt/> Additionally, to reduce the state deficit, Sharpe has called for eliminating [[unfunded mandates]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wktv.com/content/news/Larry-Sharpe-Makes-a-Stop-in-Little-Falls-490677711.html|title=Larry Sharpe Makes a Stop in Little Falls|author=Mooney, Cody|date=August 12, 2018|accessdate=August 14, 2018|publisher=[[WKTV]]}}</ref> He has vowed to follow this reduction in state spending with a reduction in [[property taxes]] and the ultimate repeal of the New York state [[income tax]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelcn.com/lcn01/governor-candidate-larry-sharpe-shares-appeal-in-area-visit-20180508|title=Governor candidate Larry Sharpe shares appeal in area visit|author=Kendrick, Jim|date=May 8, 2018|accessdate=August 14, 2018|work=Livingston County News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/eye-on-ny-larry-sharpe-libertarian-candidate-for-ny-governor/article_616f4e48-719c-11e8-8ca0-2f09abba22f8.html|title=Eye on NY: Larry Sharpe, Libertarian candidate for NY governor, brings message to Auburn|date=June 17, 2018|accessdate=August 14, 2018|author=Harding, Robert|work=auburnpub.com}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nSharpe has called for the [[decentralization]] of education in New York State and has proposed a \"K-10\" model, reducing the span of high school to ready students for the workforce and/or college.<ref name=Ithaca /><ref name=LTT>{{cite web|url=https://www.saratogatodaynewspaper.com/today-in-saratoga/education/item/8929-let-teachers-teach-with-new-york-state-governor-candidate-larry-sharpe|title=Let Teachers Teach with New York State Governor Candidate Larry Sharpe|date=August 23, 2018|accessdate=August 25, 2018|author=Mahan, Lori|work=Saratoga Today}}</ref> Sharpe has also rejected [[standardized testing]] until high school.<ref name=LTT /> He stated, \"everyone should be able to opt out of testing at any time....it puts kids who have [[special needs]] at a huge disadvantage. Kids who do not test well are labeled as dumb.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesunion.com/news/article/Three-more-gubernatorial-candidates-to-watch-12875753.php|title=3 third-party candidates for governor to watch|author=Silberstein, Rachel|date=May 2, 2018|accessdate=August 18, 2018|work=Albany Times Union}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, Sharpe stated he would refuse [[Categorical grant|federal grants]] for education. He would also abolish the [[Governing boards of colleges and universities in the United States#Regents|Board of Regents]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syracuse.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/09/staples_bridge_libertarian_gov_candidate_says_lets_lease_naming_rights_on_state.html|title=Legal weed and decentralized education: Can a Libertarian win NY's gov race?|author=Baker, Chris|date=September 17, 2018|accessdate=September 17, 2018|work=Syracuse.com}}</ref>\n\n===Gun laws===\nSharpe vowed, if elected, to repeal the [[NY SAFE Act]] by 2020 and pardon those convicted under its provisions.<ref name= paternalgovt>{{cite web|url=http://www.adirondackdailyenterprise.com/news/local-news/2018/07/sharpe-seeks-a-less-paternal-government/|title=Sharpe seeks a less paternal government|author=Crowley, Peter|date=July 7, 2018|accessdate=August 14, 2018|work=Adirondack Daily Enterprise}}</ref> Sharpe supports allowing school teachers and staff to carry firearms on school grounds, on a voluntary basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oswegocountynewsnow.com/news/ny-gov-long-shot-larry-sharpe-visits-oswego/article_feeef2dc-6e7b-11e8-ba2e-c7e21490836f.html|title=NY Gov long shot Larry Sharpe visits Oswego|author=Wallace, Lexie|date=June 13, 2018|accessdate=August 14, 2018|work=Oswego County News Now}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSharpe lives with his wife Georgia and their two children in [[Queens]], New York.<ref name=\"Meet Larry\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Sharpe mounts campaign to challenge Cuomo |url=http://www.troyrecord.com/article/TR/20180113/NEWS/180119901 |accessdate=August 10, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Contributions==\n* {{cite book|title=Igniting Liberty: Voices for Freedom Around the World|isbn=978-1793165039|author1=Barsouk, Adam|author2=Van Staden, Martin|others= Sharpe, Larry (foreword)|year=2019}}\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title=New York gubernatorial election, 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nyenr.elections.ny.gov/|title=New York State Unofficial Election Night Results|accessdate=November 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120174014/https://nyenr.elections.ny.gov/|archive-date=November 20, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = ''Andrew Cuomo''\n  |votes      = 3,158,459\n  |percentage = 54.53\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Working Families Party\n  |candidate  = ''Andrew Cuomo''\n  |votes      = 106,008\n  |percentage = 1.83\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Independence Party of New York\n  |candidate  = ''Andrew Cuomo''\n  |votes      = 63,518\n  |percentage = 1.10\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Women's Equality Party (New York)\n  |candidate  = ''Andrew Cuomo''\n  |votes      = 25,510\n  |percentage = 0.44\n}}\n|-\n! style=\"background